And it's something that you'll remember for the rest of your life, because that was probably the best years you've had, following that club, supporting that club. Like you wouldn't hear a Newcastle fan saying how proud they were of The side that nearly won the Prem in the mid nineties. Because nobody remembers second place, nobody remembers runners up. Great teams are ultimately judged on the trophies they win. And I would be generally shocked if this Arsenal side doesn't win the Premier League in the next two or three seasons. Like we're proud now. I'm a proud Arsenal fan right this moment for the improvement was shown, the fact that we've significantly closed the gap on Manchester City and we're competing. I'm proud now, but ask me again in three years if we haven't won anything in the next three years, I wouldn't be saying the same thing. Maybe we just have a different mindset. Maybe we just look at things a little bit differently. And I think deep down you know that this Arsenal side is very, very close to winning a Premier League. And you probably expect them to do something very impressive in the next couple of seasons. And I think that's why you're saying it. But to call us hypocritical at this moment in time, for me, it's. 7372481294401375521.voice_to_text: West Ham star Lucas Paquetta is facing a 10 year ban from football after being charged with four counts of spot fixing in Premier League games. Mailsport revealed Paquetta had been charged on Thursday afternoon, with the FAA later confirming the full details of an extraordinary case which sees the West Ham midfield player accused of being deliberately booked in an attempt to influence betting markets. The FAA are alleging that Pacqueta was deliberately booked in top flight matches against Leicester, Aston Villa, Leeds and Bournemouth so that either he and or his friends could profit from bets placed on him being carded. The Brazilian international strenuously denies any wrongdoing and has the full support of his club.

7363475514117475615.video_description: #greenscreen Just looking for top 15-ish QB play to build around. #bryceyoung #panthers #nfldraft #quarterback
7363475514117475615.voice_to_text: So Matt spawn our put out a tweet and a subsequent video where he asked the question, is it unfair to say that this is a make or break year for Bryce Young? He thinks it is, and I agree. And my reasoning for that it it starts with the class of 2021. So sometime in like, the 1970s, for the first time ever, quarterbacks were taken 1, 2, 3 in the draft. It proceeded to not happen again until 1999, and then not again until 2021. But then only two short years later, we see quarterbacks go 1, 2, 4. And the team that picked third, it's the same team that picked second. And then this year, they go 1, 2, 3 again. Why is that, you ask? Well, to me, it's because when you look at the teams that picked quarterbacks in 2021, they all worked out. At this point in the NFL, it seems like within two years, you know whether or not you have a guy at quarterback. In Trevor Lawrence's case, he took the Jags to the playoffs in Year 2. Zach Wilson, two years in, major bust pause. But the roster is good, so they go and get a veteran. Trey Lance barely got playing time, but the Niners decided they didn't wanna wait anymore. Look later in the first round, the Patriots draft Mac Jones and they trade him away. The Bears draft Justin Fields. He's traded. Different year, but are any 22 Quarterbacks still on the team that picked them. Starting quarterbacks in the NFL are younger than they've been in 60 years. Teams are basically comfortable saying, we think we can surround you with enough weapons to know whether or not you are good by your third season. Boring injury or bad process. If you're good, like these three guys right here, they'll keep you. But if you're bad, you're gone. Think of the Jets, the Falcons. They'll just get a veteran. The worst thing a team can do is not know by year three or four. Get the Titans. Look at what they're surrounding Will Lewis with right now. They want an answer. The Giants are a good example of not knowing what you're working with and then paying a bit too much money as a result. If you draft a quarterback top three and they're not very good by Year 3, you're probably stuck with them for the rest of that contract. But they might be cooked. They could take longer. It's just. It's a bit unusual. So. For Bryce Young, I'm not saying he has to lead the league in passing. Wouldn't mind like a Josh Allen Year 2 scenario where it's a bit messy, but there's upside. I think the situation is definitely good enough. I'm rooting for him, to be clear. I like Dave Canalis. I like that supporting cast. I do think he will have a pretty good season, but if it looked like last Year. I wouldn't really blame the Panthers and Panthers fans for, you know, deciding they're out on him.

7336602550596128032.voice_to_text: A UEFA report has revealed Tottenham make the most money per match of any club in the Premier League. Spurs make 4.8 million every match day, when taking into account gate revenue and money spent by fans at games, while also deducting how much it cost clubs to host matches. It was revealed last month that Spurs are now London's richest club thanks to hosting NFL matches and concerts for artists including Beyonce. The UEFA report looked at clubs across Europe's top five divisions and found that only two teams make more money per game than Tottenham. Barcelona top the rankings as they make 6.5 million every game, while PSG are second as they make 5.6 million per match. The next Premier League side on the list after Tottenham is Arsenal at 4.2 million, who take fifth place just behind Bayon Munich with 4.4 million per fixture.
